{"parentUuid":"48b62c37-c484-4f89-bff5-64c68740e979","isSidechain":true,"agentId":"aa28e0abdc3b5ed74","message":{"model":"claude-opus-4-8","id":"msg_01JFByNom9gxEpAJxLiDX6TL","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"tool_use","id":"toolu_01RVPU5r633dpuqvNB4DR7iF","name":"WebFetch","input":{"url":"https://insiderllm.com/guides/fine-tuning-mac-lora-mlx/","prompt":"Extract concrete memory figures and training times for LoRA and QLoRA fine-tuning of different model sizes (1B, 3B, 7B, 8B) on Apple Silicon, especially for 16GB machines. What model sizes fit in 16GB? What framework is recommended? How is the adapter served afterward (merge to GGUF, Ollama)?"},"caller":{"type":"direct"}}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":2,"cache_creation_input_tokens":4025,"cache_read_input_tokens":12545,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":4025,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":0},"output_tokens":4,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"diagnostics":null},"requestId":"req_011CcFivKnruoAx9uaUauCpY","attributionAgent":"general-purpose","type":"assistant","uuid":"24387189-a67b-434f-b678-dc5c7621ee8e","timestamp":"2026-06-21T03:50:09.976Z","userType":"external","entrypoint":"cli","cwd":"/Users/gg/Work/Yogi","sessionId":"d8d6b712-ec33-4776-a194-d9a72216a25f","version":"2.1.183","gitBranch":"main"}
{"parentUuid":"24387189-a67b-434f-b678-dc5c7621ee8e","isSidechain":true,"agentId":"aa28e0abdc3b5ed74","message":{"model":"claude-opus-4-8","id":"msg_01JFByNom9gxEpAJxLiDX6TL","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"tool_use","id":"toolu_01NfTfvMWmETvT5r83UMov1H","name":"WebSearch","input":{"query":"MLX-LM fuse adapter merge GGUF Ollama serve LoRA Qwen3"},"caller":{"type":"direct"}}],"stop_reason":"tool_use","stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":2,"cache_creation_input_tokens":4025,"cache_read_input_tokens":12545,"output_tokens":319,"server_tool_use":{"web_search_requests":0,"web_fetch_requests":0},"service_tier":"standard","cache_creation":{"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":4025},"inference_geo":"not_available","iterations":[{"input_tokens":2,"output_tokens":319,"cache_read_input_tokens":12545,"cache_creation_input_tokens":4025,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":4025,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":0},"type":"message"}],"speed":"standard"},"diagnostics":null},"requestId":"req_011CcFivKnruoAx9uaUauCpY","attributionAgent":"general-purpose","type":"assistant","uuid":"349734d7-f92a-4e64-8921-e2d5c671c91d","timestamp":"2026-06-21T03:50:10.108Z","userType":"external","entrypoint":"cli","cwd":"/Users/gg/Work/Yogi","sessionId":"d8d6b712-ec33-4776-a194-d9a72216a25f","version":"2.1.183","gitBranch":"main"}
{"parentUuid":"349734d7-f92a-4e64-8921-e2d5c671c91d","isSidechain":true,"promptId":"ed988829-c186-4cf7-8fda-2a36bf7006f0","agentId":"aa28e0abdc3b5ed74","type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01NfTfvMWmETvT5r83UMov1H","type":"tool_result","content":"Web search results for query: \"MLX-LM fuse adapter merge GGUF Ollama serve LoRA Qwen3\"\n\nLinks: [{\"title\":\"Converting LoRA (adapters.safetensors) to GGUF · ml-explore/mlx · Discussion #1507\",\"url\":\"https://github.com/ml-explore/mlx/discussions/1507\"},{\"title\":\"mlx-lm/mlx_lm/LORA.md at main · ml-explore/mlx-lm\",\"url\":\"https://github.com/ml-explore/mlx-lm/blob/main/mlx_lm/LORA.md\"},{\"title\":\"Fine-Tuning on Mac: LoRA & QLoRA with MLX | InsiderLLM\",\"url\":\"https://insiderllm.com/guides/fine-tuning-mac-lora-mlx/\"},{\"title\":\"Build Your Own LLM with LLM Fine-Tuning on MacOS Using MLX\",\"url\":\"https://medium.com/rahasak/fine-tuning-llms-on-macos-using-mlx-and-run-with-ollama-182a20f1fd2c\"},{\"title\":\"MLX to GGUF conversion · Issue #353 · ml-explore/mlx-lm\",\"url\":\"https://github.com/ml-explore/mlx-lm/issues/353\"},{\"title\":\"Bringing Your Fine-Tuned MLX Model to Life with Ollama Integration | by Meir Michanie | Medium\",\"url\":\"https://medium.com/@meirgotroot/bringing-your-fine-tuned-mlx-model-to-life-with-ollama-integration-c54274de6491\"},{\"title\":\"Fine-tuning Llama 3 on macOS with MLX for Ollama Deployment | by Soumyajit Swain | Medium\",\"url\":\"https://medium.com/@soumyajit.swain/fine-tuning-llama-3-on-macos-with-mlx-for-ollama-deployment-6a1c0c8ddb1b\"},{\"title\":\"AI trading agent: Fusing LoRA adapters for Ollama - Chainstack\",\"url\":\"https://docs.chainstack.com/docs/ai-trading-agent-fusing-llm-adapters-and-converting-to-ollama\"},{\"title\":\"Qwen3.5 4B(merged LORA adapter) convert to MLX generates incorrect results · Issue #1058 · ml-explore/mlx-lm\",\"url\":\"https://github.com/ml-explore/mlx-lm/issues/1058\"}]\n\nBased on the search results, here's what I found regarding MLX-LM, fusing adapters, merging to GGUF, and serving with Ollama:\n\n## Key Workflow\n\nTo use the model with Ollama, you need to fuse the adapters into the base model and convert to GGUF. The typical workflow involves:\n\n1. **Fusing LoRA Adapters**: Use `mlx_lm.fuse` with the `--de-quantize` flag if you trained with QLoRA, which converts the fused model back to fp16, needed for clean GGUF conversion.\n\n2. **Converting to GGUF**: The `mlx_lm.fuse` command can produce a GGUF file (fp16) in the output directory. However, GGUF export currently works with Llama, Mistral, and Mixtral architectures. For other architectures, use llama.cpp's convert_hf_to_gguf.py on the fused safetensors model.\n\n3. **Serving with Ollama**: Ollama uses a Modelfile to define how a model should be loaded, pointing to the relative or absolute path of your GGUF file.\n\n## Qwen3 Considerations\n\nFor Qwen3.5-4B LoRA adapters merged with the base model and converted to MLX format, there have been reports of the MLX version producing different output compared to the original HuggingFace Transformers version.\n\nThe search results show working examples with Llama, Mistral, and other standard architectures, but Qwen3 appears to have some compatibility considerations during the conversion process.\n\n\nREMINDER: You MUST include the sources above in your response to the user using markdown hyperlinks."}]},"uuid":"a5caf29e-524a-476c-86c6-68114dc40270","timestamp":"2026-06-21T03:50:17.437Z","toolUseResult":{"query":"MLX-LM fuse adapter merge GGUF Ollama serve LoRA Qwen3","results":[{"tool_use_id":"srvtoolu_0142Zuy7ZKppw6YGuQ5Vwjkx","content":[{"title":"Converting LoRA (adapters.safetensors) to GGUF · ml-explore/mlx · Discussion #1507","url":"https://github.com/ml-explore/mlx/discussions/1507"},{"title":"mlx-lm/mlx_lm/LORA.md at main · ml-explore/mlx-lm","url":"https://github.com/ml-explore/mlx-lm/blob/main/mlx_lm/LORA.md"},{"title":"Fine-Tuning on Mac: LoRA & QLoRA with MLX | InsiderLLM","url":"https://insiderllm.com/guides/fine-tuning-mac-lora-mlx/"},{"title":"Build Your Own LLM with LLM Fine-Tuning on MacOS Using MLX","url":"https://medium.com/rahasak/fine-tuning-llms-on-macos-using-mlx-and-run-with-ollama-182a20f1fd2c"},{"title":"MLX to GGUF conversion · Issue #353 · ml-explore/mlx-lm","url":"https://github.com/ml-explore/mlx-lm/issues/353"},{"title":"Bringing Your Fine-Tuned MLX Model to Life with Ollama Integration | by Meir Michanie | Medium","url":"https://medium.com/@meirgotroot/bringing-your-fine-tuned-mlx-model-to-life-with-ollama-integration-c54274de6491"},{"title":"Fine-tuning Llama 3 on macOS with MLX for Ollama Deployment | by Soumyajit Swain | Medium","url":"https://medium.com/@soumyajit.swain/fine-tuning-llama-3-on-macos-with-mlx-for-ollama-deployment-6a1c0c8ddb1b"},{"title":"AI trading agent: Fusing LoRA adapters for Ollama - Chainstack","url":"https://docs.chainstack.com/docs/ai-trading-agent-fusing-llm-adapters-and-converting-to-ollama"},{"title":"Qwen3.5 4B(merged LORA adapter) convert to MLX generates incorrect results · Issue #1058 · ml-explore/mlx-lm","url":"https://github.com/ml-explore/mlx-lm/issues/1058"}]},"Based on the search results, here's what I found regarding MLX-LM, fusing adapters, merging to GGUF, and serving with Ollama:\n\n## Key Workflow\n\nTo use the model with Ollama, you need to fuse the adapters into the base model and convert to GGUF. The typical workflow involves:\n\n1. **Fusing LoRA Adapters**: Use `mlx_lm.fuse` with the `--de-quantize` flag if you trained with QLoRA, which converts the fused model back to fp16, needed for clean GGUF conversion.\n\n2. **Converting to GGUF**: The `mlx_lm.fuse` command can produce a GGUF file (fp16) in the output directory. However, GGUF export currently works with Llama, Mistral, and Mixtral architectures. For other architectures, use llama.cpp's convert_hf_to_gguf.py on the fused safetensors model.\n\n3. **Serving with Ollama**: Ollama uses a Modelfile to define how a model should be loaded, pointing to the relative or absolute path of your GGUF file.\n\n## Qwen3 Considerations\n\nFor Qwen3.5-4B LoRA adapters merged with the base model and converted to MLX format, there have been reports of the MLX version producing different output compared to the original HuggingFace Transformers version.\n\nThe search results show working examples with Llama, Mistral, and other standard architectures, but Qwen3 appears to have some compatibility considerations during the conversion process."],"durationSeconds":7.136290582999995,"searchCount":1},"sourceToolAssistantUUID":"349734d7-f92a-4e64-8921-e2d5c671c91d","userType":"external","entrypoint":"cli","cwd":"/Users/gg/Work/Yogi","sessionId":"d8d6b712-ec33-4776-a194-d9a72216a25f","version":"2.1.183","gitBranch":"main"}
{"parentUuid":"24387189-a67b-434f-b678-dc5c7621ee8e","isSidechain":true,"promptId":"ed988829-c186-4cf7-8fda-2a36bf7006f0","agentId":"aa28e0abdc3b5ed74","type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01RVPU5r633dpuqvNB4DR7iF","type":"tool_result","content":"# LoRA/QLoRA Memory Requirements for 16GB Apple Silicon Macs\n\n## Supported Model Sizes\n\nAccording to the guide's hardware compatibility table, a **16GB Mac can handle**:\n- **LoRA (full precision):** 3B-7B models\n- **QLoRA (4-bit quantized):** 7B-8B models\n\nThe framework described as having \"workable\" performance at this memory tier uses approximately 200 tokens/second training speed.\n\n## Framework & Installation\n\nThe recommended approach uses **MLX** (Apple's machine learning framework). Setup is minimal:\n```\npip install \"mlx-lm[train]\"\n```\n\nThe guide emphasizes that MLX's unified memory architecture eliminates separate VRAM constraints—unlike NVIDIA GPUs with fixed VRAM pools.\n\n## Training Specifications for 16GB\n\n- **Training command:** `mlx_lm.lora --model [name] --train --data [path] --iters 500`\n- **Typical dataset:** 200-500 examples in JSONL format\n- **Training duration:** Roughly 15-45 minutes for 500 iterations on an 8B model, depending on sequence length\n\n## Deployment: Adapter Fusion & GGUF Export\n\nPost-training deployment follows this sequence:\n\n1. **Fuse adapters** into the base model using `mlx_lm.fuse`\n2. **Export to GGUF format** (fp16) via `--export-gguf` flag\n3. **Quantize the GGUF** for practical file sizes (~16GB uncompressed for 8B models)\n4. **Deploy via Ollama** by creating a Modelfile pointing to the quantized GGUF\n\nThe final model becomes accessible through \"Ollama's API, accessible by any tool that speaks the Ollama or OpenAI-compatible protocol.\""}]},"uuid":"17e710e0-e936-4fb6-9e8e-620c4024fe8d","timestamp":"2026-06-21T03:50:20.581Z","toolUseResult":{"bytes":41990,"code":200,"codeText":"OK","result":"# LoRA/QLoRA Memory Requirements for 16GB Apple Silicon Macs\n\n## Supported Model Sizes\n\nAccording to the guide's hardware compatibility table, a **16GB Mac can handle**:\n- **LoRA (full precision):** 3B-7B models\n- **QLoRA (4-bit quantized):** 7B-8B models\n\nThe framework described as having \"workable\" performance at this memory tier uses approximately 200 tokens/second training speed.\n\n## Framework & Installation\n\nThe recommended approach uses **MLX** (Apple's machine learning framework). Setup is minimal:\n```\npip install \"mlx-lm[train]\"\n```\n\nThe guide emphasizes that MLX's unified memory architecture eliminates separate VRAM constraints—unlike NVIDIA GPUs with fixed VRAM pools.\n\n## Training Specifications for 16GB\n\n- **Training command:** `mlx_lm.lora --model [name] --train --data [path] --iters 500`\n- **Typical dataset:** 200-500 examples in JSONL format\n- **Training duration:** Roughly 15-45 minutes for 500 iterations on an 8B model, depending on sequence length\n\n## Deployment: Adapter Fusion & GGUF Export\n\nPost-training deployment follows this sequence:\n\n1. **Fuse adapters** into the base model using `mlx_lm.fuse`\n2. **Export to GGUF format** (fp16) via `--export-gguf` flag\n3. **Quantize the GGUF** for practical file sizes (~16GB uncompressed for 8B models)\n4. **Deploy via Ollama** by creating a Modelfile pointing to the quantized GGUF\n\nThe final model becomes accessible through \"Ollama's API, accessible by any tool that speaks the Ollama or OpenAI-compatible protocol.\"","durationMs":10368,"url":"https://insiderllm.com/guides/fine-tuning-mac-lora-mlx/"},"sourceToolAssistantUUID":"24387189-a67b-434f-b678-dc5c7621ee8e","userType":"external","entrypoint":"cli","cwd":"/Users/gg/Work/Yogi","sessionId":"d8d6b712-ec33-4776-a194-d9a72216a25f","version":"2.1.183","gitBranch":"main"}
